properties.areaDesc: Bannock, ID; Bear Lake, ID; Caribou, ID; Franklin, ID; Oneida, ID; Power, ID
properties.headline: Hydrologic Outlook issued April 25 at 2:02PM MDT by NWS Pocatello ID
properties.description:
Enhanced snowmelt is likely this week as warmer temperatures
spread into the region. By this weekend, daytime highs will reach
into the 40s in the mountains, approach 60 degrees in mountain
valleys, and reach into the upper 70s across the Snake Plain and
eastern Magic Valley. Additionally, rain on snow yesterday has
increased melting rates in select areas. Small creeks and streams
could overflow along with additional ponding of lowland farmland
where appreciable snow is still left to melt. Resultant flooding
could impact agricultural interests along with area roads, homes,
and businesses. Increased releases on small reservoirs are also
possible, which could produce significant rises downstream on area
streams and rivers.

Clear snow, ice and debris from culverts and other flow paths to
allow runoff to flow away from buildings and other vulnerable
infrastructure. Move deep snow away from the foundations of
buildings, and move equipment and livestock out of poorly drained
or low lying areas. Remember, if you encounter a flooded roadway,
turn around don't drown, you never know what road conditions are
hidden under the water.  Report any flooding to county officials.

NWSheadline: Increased Snowmelt and Flooding Possible this Week

properties.headline: Flood Advisory issued April 25 at 1:36PM MDT until April 27 at 3:00PM MDT by NWS Pocatello ID
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by snowmelt continues.

* WHERE...Franklin County in southeast Idaho.

* WHEN...Until 300 PM MDT Thursday.

* IMPACTS...Minor flooding in low-lying and poor drainage areas.
Streams and creeks running high. Water over a few back roadways.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 119 PM MDT, Local law enforcement and emergency management
personnel reported that minor flooding due to snowmelt
continues across the advisory area. Many fields have standing
water, creeks and streams are running high, and a few back
roads are affected.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Preston, Franklin, Oneida Narrows Reservoir, Thatcher,
Dayton, Weston, Clifton, Oxford, Riverdale, Mink Creek,
Whitney, Mapleton and Emmigrant Summit.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

Please report observed flooding to local emergency services or law
enforcement and request they pass this information to the National
Weather Service when you can do so safely.

ground pipes to protect them from freezing.

properties.description:

between 8 and 16 inches, with local amounts to 28 inches for
favored areas.

* WHERE...Front Range mountains, including Rocky Mountain NP, the
Indian Peaks Wilderness, and the Eisenhower Tunnel, in addition to

heavy snowfall on roadways. The hazardous conditions could impact

properties.instruction:
Monitor the latest forecasts for updates on this situation.

Persons should consider delaying travel. If travel is absolutely
necessary, drive with extreme caution. Consider taking a winter
storm kit along with you, including such items as tire chains,
booster cables, flashlight, shovel, blankets and extra clothing.
Also take water, a first aid kit, and anything else that would help
you survive in case you become stranded.

properties.description:
* WHAT...Minor flooding is occurring and minor flooding is forecast.

* WHERE...Pearl River Near Bogalusa.

* WHEN...Until early Thursday morning.

* IMPACTS...At 20.0 feet, Woodlands and crop acreage along the river
will be flooded. The Bogue Chitto Wildlife Management area will be
inundated with water in recreational camps and over access roads.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 12:00 PM CDT Tuesday the stage was 20.3 feet.
- Recent Activity...The maximum river stage in the 24 hours
ending at 12:00 PM CDT Tuesday was 20.4 feet.
- Forecast...The river is expected to fall below flood stage
tomorrow evening and continue falling to 11.6 feet Friday,
May 05.
- Flood stage is 18.0 feet.
- Flood History...This crest compares to a previous crest of
20.3 feet on 04/15/2000.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood

* WHEN...Until Saturday morning.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...

- Recent Activity...The maximum river stage in the 24 hours

- Forecast...The river is expected to fall below flood stage

Friday, May 05.

16.3 feet on 02/15/2005.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood

properties.description:
RRA

* WHAT...Flooding caused by snowmelt continues.

* WHERE...A portion of northeast North Dakota, including the
following county, Walsh.

* WHEN...Until 400 PM CDT Friday.

* IMPACTS...Flooding of rivers, creeks, streams, and other low-lying
and flood-prone locations is imminent or occurring.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 1154 AM CDT, satellite imagery continues to indicate
overland flooding, particularly within eastern Walsh County.
Emergency management recently reported overland flooding from
snow melt.
- Ongoing snowmelt will continue to lead to widespread flooding
impacts through at least Friday. This may include road
closures, washouts, and other snowmelt related flooding
impacts.  Precipitation may exacerbate these impacts.
properties.instruction:
Safety message - Turn around, don't drown. Don't travel through
flooded areas. Most flood deaths occur in vehicles.

properties.areaDesc: Northern Sangre de Cristo Mountains Between 8500 And 11000 Ft; Northern Sangre de Cristo Mountains above 11000 Ft; Southern Sangre De Cristo Mountains Between 7500 and 11000 Ft; Pikes Peak above 11000 Ft
properties.headline: Avalanche Advisory issued April 25 at 10:34AM MDT by NWS Denver CO
properties.description:
THE FOLLOWING MESSAGE IS TRANSMITTED AT THE REQUEST OF THE
COLORADO AVALANCHE INFORMATION CENTER.

SPECIAL AVALANCHE ADVISORY IN EFFECT FROM 4:30 PM TUESDAY UNTIL 4:30 PM THURSDAY

*WHAT A potent spring storm is impacting the area creating dangerous avalanche
conditions. Strong easterly winds and heavy snowfall will result in a Considerable
(Level 3 of 5) danger.

*WHERE Sangre de Cristo Mountains and Pikes Peak

*WHEN Expect dangerous avalanche conditions to begin on Tuesday night by about
midnight and last through Thursday

*IMPACTS Heavy snow and strong winds will create dangerous avalanche conditions.
Large and dangerous avalanches will be easy to trigger once the new snow accumualtes.
Avalanches will run naturally.

*PRECAUTIONARY / PREPAREDNESS ACTIONS Careful snowpack evaluation, cautious
route-finding, and conservative decision-making is essential. You can find more
detailed information at colorado.gov/avalanche

Gibson

properties.headline: Rip Current Statement issued April 25 at 11:29AM CDT until April 26 at 7:00AM CDT by NWS Corpus Christi TX
properties.description:
* WHAT...For the Coastal Flood Advisory, minor coastal flooding.
For the High Rip Current Risk, dangerous rip currents.

* WHERE...Aransas Islands, Kleberg Islands, Nueces Islands and
Calhoun Islands Counties.

* WHEN...For the Coastal Flood Advisory, until 7 PM CDT this
evening. For the High Rip Current Risk, through Wednesday
morning.

* IMPACTS...Flooding of lots, parks, and roads with only
isolated road closures expected. Rip currents can sweep even
the most experienced swimmers away from shore into deeper
water. These rip currents can become life-threatening to
anyone entering the surf.
properties.instruction:
If travel is required, allow extra time as some roads may be
closed. Do not drive around barricades or through water of
unknown depth. Take the necessary actions to protect flood-prone
property.

Swim near a lifeguard. If caught in a rip current, relax and
float. Don't swim against the current. If able, swim in a
direction following the shoreline. If unable to escape, face the
shore and call or wave for help.

properties.areaDesc: Southern Graham-Central and Eastern Cochise-Southern Greenlee-Lower Elevations of the San Carlos Apache Nation in Graham County
properties.headline: Red Flag Warning issued April 25 at 3:15AM MST until April 25 at 7:00PM MST by NWS Tucson AZ
properties.description:
* AFFECTED AREA...Fire Weather Zone 152, which includes the lower
elevations of Graham and Greenlee counties and the eastern two
thirds of Cochise county.

* TIMING...2 pm this afternoon until 7 pm this evening.

* WINDS...West to northwest 20-foot winds 20 to 25 mph with gusts
between 35 and 45 mph. Strongest likely in the Gila valley.

* RELATIVE HUMIDITY..As low as 8 to 15 percent.

* IMPACTS...Any fires that develop or are ongoing will have the
potential to spread rapidly.

* FOR A DETAILED VIEW OF THE HAZARD AREA...Visit
weather.gov/Tucson and click on the Detailed Hazards Icon.
properties.instruction:
A Red Flag Warning means that critical fire weather conditions are
either occurring now, or are expected to develop. A combination of
strong winds, low relative humidity and dry dead vegetation will
create the potential for rapid and erratic fire growth.

Please advise the appropriate officials or fire crews in the
field of the Red Flag Warning for portions of Southeast Arizona.

NWSheadline: RED FLAG WARNING REMAINS IN EFFECT FROM 2 PM THIS AFTERNOON TO 7 PM MST THIS EVENING FOR STRONG AND GUSTY WINDS, LOW RELATIVE HUMIDITY AND HIGH FIRE WEATHER DANGER FOR FIRE WEATHER ZONE 152

properties.areaDesc: Juneau, WI
properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 25 at 4:44AM CDT until April 25 at 10:00PM CDT by NWS La Crosse WI
properties.description:
* WHAT...Minor flooding is occurring and minor flooding is forecast.

* WHERE...Yellow River at Necedah.

* WHEN...Until late this evening.

* IMPACTS...The combination of snow melt and rainfall has resulted
minor
flooding along the Yellow River at Necedah.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 2:00 AM CDT Tuesday the stage was 14.9 feet.
- Recent Activity...The maximum river stage in the 24 hours
ending at 4:00 AM CDT Monday was 15.7 feet.
- Forecast...The river is near flood stage. It will then fall
below flood stage early this morning to 14.6 feet this
morning. It will rise to 14.8 feet this evening. It will then
fall again and remain below flood stage.
- Flood stage is 15.0 feet.
- Flood History...This crest compares to a previous crest of
15.7 feet on 05/10/2012.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood

* WHERE...Southeastern Coconino, southern Apache, and southern
Navajo counties, including Happy Jack, Winslow, Snowflake, Show
Low, St. Johns, Window Rock, and Tuba City.

* WHEN...From 8 AM MST /9 AM MDT/ this morning to 8 PM MST /9 PM

profile vehicle. Secure outdoor objects.

properties.areaDesc: Coastal Franklin
properties.headline: Rip Current Statement issued April 25 at 4:40AM EDT until April 25 at 11:00PM EDT by NWS Tallahassee FL
properties.description:
* WHAT...Dangerous rip currents.

* WHERE...Franklin County Beaches.

* WHEN...Through this evening.

* IMPACTS...Rip currents can sweep even the best swimmers away
from shore into deeper water.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Fresh easterly breezes across the northeast
Gulf last night churned up the waters. Franklin County beaches
will be open to the surf and high rip current risk that the
east winds kicked up.
properties.instruction:
Swim near a lifeguard. If caught in a rip current, relax and
float. Don't swim against the current. If able, swim in a
direction following the shoreline. If unable to escape, face the
shore and call or wave for help.

properties.areaDesc: Kenedy Island; Willacy Island; Cameron Island
properties.headline: Coastal Flood Advisory issued April 25 at 3:10AM CDT until April 25 at 5:00PM CDT by NWS Brownsville TX
properties.description:
* WHAT...For the High Rip Current Risk, dangerous rip currents.
For the Coastal Flood Advisory, minor coastal flooding
expected.

* WHERE...Kenedy Island, Willacy Island and Cameron Island
Counties.

* WHEN...For the High Rip Current Risk, through Wednesday
morning. For the Coastal Flood Advisory, from 8 AM this
morning to 5 PM CDT this afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Nuisance flooding is expected, with water reaching or
pushing into the dunes on South Padre Island. Vehicles, except
those with four wheel drive and high wheel bases, will be unable
to be driven on the beach. This includes locations north of
Public Beach Access #3. Minor to moderate beach erosion is
expected. Rip currents can sweep even the best swimmers away
from shore into deeper water.
properties.instruction:
If travel is required, allow extra time as some roads may be
closed. Do not drive around barricades or through water of
unknown depth. Take the necessary actions to protect flood-prone
property.

Swim near a lifeguard. If caught in a rip current, relax and
float. Don't swim against the current. If able, swim in a
direction following the shoreline. If unable to escape, face the
shore and call or wave for help.

NWSheadline: HIGH RIP CURRENT RISK NOW IN EFFECT THROUGH WEDNESDAY MORNING... ...COASTAL FLOOD ADVISORY IN EFFECT FROM 8 AM THIS MORNING TO 5 PM CDT THIS AFTERNOON

properties.headline: Freeze Watch issued April 24 at 8:28PM CDT until April 26 at 8:00AM CDT by NWS Quad Cities IA IL
properties.description:
* WHAT...Sub-freezing temperatures in the upper 20s to lower 30s
are possible.

* WHERE...Portions of north central and northwest Illinois and
east central and northeast Iowa.

* WHEN...From late Tuesday night through Wednesday morning.

* IMPACTS...Frost and freeze conditions could kill crops, other
sensitive vegetation and possibly damage unprotected outdoor
plumbing.
properties.instruction:
Take steps now to protect tender plants from the cold. To prevent
freezing and possible bursting of outdoor water pipes they should
be wrapped, drained, or allowed to drip slowly. Those that have
in-ground sprinkler systems should drain them and cover above-
ground pipes to protect them from freezing.

properties.areaDesc: Elko, NV
properties.headline: Flood Advisory issued April 24 at 5:16PM PDT until April 27 at 5:00AM PDT by NWS Elko NV
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by snowmelt is occurring.

* WHERE...A portion of northeast Nevada, including the following
county, Elko.

* WHEN...Until 500 AM PDT Thursday.

* IMPACTS...Minor flooding in low-lying and poor drainage areas.
Water over roadways. Some low-water crossings may become
impassable. River or stream flows are elevated.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 516 PM PDT, Nevada Department of Transportation reported
flooding in SR-226 near MM 15. Overflowing poor drainage
areas have already caused minor flooding in SR-226 near MM
15.
- SR-226 near MM 15 is the most likely place to experience
minor flooding.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
mainly rural areas of Western Elko County
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

Be especially cautious at night when it is harder to recognize the
dangers of flooding.

Be aware of your surroundings and do not drive on flooded roads.

In hilly terrain there are hundreds of low water crossings which are
potentially dangerous in heavy rain. Do not attempt to cross flooded
roads. Find an alternate route.

properties.areaDesc: Yuma, AZ
properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 24 at 4:49PM MST until May 2 at 5:00PM MST by NWS Phoenix AZ
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by upstream dam release is expected.

* WHERE...A portion of southwest Arizona, including the following
county, Yuma.

* WHEN...Until 500 PM MST Tuesday May 02.

* IMPACTS...Lowland flooding and inundation of unbridged crossings
will occur along the Gila River downstream of Painted Rock Dam.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 439 PM MST, water being released from Painted Rock Dam
continues to travel down the Gila River through Yuma County.
This will likely flood unbridged river crossings and may
inundate some farmland.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Ligurta and Kinter.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

properties.areaDesc: Surprise Valley California; Lassen-Eastern Plumas-Eastern Sierra Counties; Greater Lake Tahoe Area; Mono; Mineral and Southern Lyon Counties; Greater Lake Tahoe Area; Greater Reno-Carson City-Minden Area
properties.headline: Flood Watch issued April 24 at 2:36PM PDT until May 1 at 9:00AM PDT by NWS Reno NV
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by snowmelt is possible.

* WHERE...Portions of California and western Nevada, including the
following areas, in California, Greater Lake Tahoe Area,
Lassen-Eastern Plumas-Eastern Sierra Counties, Mono County and
Surprise Valley California. In western Nevada, Greater Lake Tahoe
Area, Greater Reno-Carson City-Minden Area and Mineral and
Southern Lyon Counties.

* WHEN...From Thursday afternoon through Monday morning.

* IMPACTS...Creeks and streams will be running high and fast.
Low-water crossings may be flooded. Minor mainstem flooding is
currently forecast along the Forks of the Carson River beginning
late Friday. The Susan and Walker Rivers will also need to be
closely monitored as flooding cannot be ruled out. Anyone
participating in outdoor recreation this weekend should use
caution as water will be running high, fast, and potentially out
of banks for some creeks and streams. The water will be extremely
cold as well, quickly causing shock.


* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
You should monitor later forecasts and be alert for possible Flood
Warnings. Those living in areas prone to flooding should be prepared
to take action should flooding develop.

properties.headline: Winter Storm Warning issued April 24 at 1:45PM MDT until April 26 at 12:00PM MDT by NWS Denver CO
properties.description:
* WHAT...Heavy snow expected. Widespread storm total accumulations
between 8 and 16 inches, with local amounts to 25 inches for
favored areas.

* WHERE...Front Range mountains, including Rocky Mountain NP, the
Indian Peaks Wilderness, and the Eisenhower Tunnel, in addition to
foothill areas above 7,500 ft. Highest potential for 2 ft snow
totals for the upper elevations of Park, Jefferson and Clear Creek
Counties.

* WHEN...From Tuesday morning through Wednesday morning. Heaviest
snowfall expected from mid afternoon Tuesday through daybreak
Wednesday.

* IMPACTS...Travel may become very difficult to impossible due to
heavy snowfall on roadways. The hazardous conditions could impact
the Tuesday evening commute.
properties.instruction:
Monitor the latest forecasts for updates on this situation.

Persons should consider delaying travel. If travel is absolutely
necessary, drive with extreme caution. Consider taking a winter
storm kit along with you, including such items as tire chains,
booster cables, flashlight, shovel, blankets and extra clothing.
Also take water, a first aid kit, and anything else that would help
you survive in case you become stranded.

properties.areaDesc: Bannock, ID; Bear Lake, ID; Caribou, ID; Franklin, ID; Oneida, ID; Power, ID
properties.headline: Hydrologic Outlook issued April 24 at 10:24AM MDT by NWS Pocatello ID
properties.description:
Enhanced snowmelt is likely this week as warmer temperatures
spread into the region. Additionally, a quarter to over three
quarters of an inch of rainfall is possible with shower and
thunderstorm activity today with elevated snow levels near 7500
feet MSL. Small creeks and streams could overflow along with
additional ponding of lowland farmland where appreciable snow is
still left to melt. Resultant flooding could impact agricultural
interests along with area roads, homes, and businesses. Increased
releases on small reservoirs are also possible, which could
produce significant rises downstream on area streams and rivers.

Clear snow, ice and debris from culverts and other flow paths to
allow runoff to flow away from buildings and other vulnerable
infrastructure. Move deep snow away from the foundations of
buildings, and move equipment and livestock out of poorly drained
or low lying areas. Remember, if you encounter a flooded roadway,
turn around don't drown, you never know what road conditions are
hidden under the water.  Report any flooding to county officials.

NWSheadline: Increased Snowmelt and Flooding Possible this Week

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued April 24 at 9:34AM MDT by NWS Albuquerque NM
properties.description:
Warm temperatures over northern mountain snowpack are driving
rapid runoff. Creeks and rivers in the mountains will experience
rapid rises. Mountain roads may experience localized flooding.

HAZARD...Rising creeks and rivers. Possible localized flooding.

IMPACT...Potential for impassable roads at high elevations.

Locations impacted include...
All rivers and creeks in the Sangre de Cristo and Tusas mountains.
All northern tributaries of the Rio Grande.
properties.instruction:

drive through flooded roadways. Be wary of rock and mudslides in
steep locations.

* WHERE...Rio Grande At Laredo.

properties.areaDesc: Nueces, TX
properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 24 at 8:37AM CDT until April 25 at 11:00PM CDT by NWS Corpus Christi TX
properties.description:
* WHAT...Moderate flooding is occurring and moderate flooding is
forecast.

* WHERE...Oso Creek Near Corpus Christi.

* WHEN...Until late tomorrow evening.

* IMPACTS...At 20.0 feet, Moderate lowland flooding occurs, from the
headwaters near Violet Road, or Farm to Market 24, to Oso Bay.
Secondary roads and low bridges near the creek are also flooded.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 7:15 AM CDT Monday the stage was 21.9 feet.
- Recent Activity...The maximum river stage in the 24 hours
ending at 7:15 AM CDT Monday was 21.9 feet.
- Forecast...The river is expected to fall below flood stage
tomorrow morning and continue falling to 7.2 feet Saturday
morning.
- Flood stage is 20.0 feet.
- Flood History...This crest compares to a previous crest of
21.9 feet on 05/23/1993.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood

NWSheadline: FLOOD WARNING NOW IN EFFECT UNTIL LATE TOMORROW EVENING

properties.areaDesc: Northwest Plateau; West Central Mountains
properties.headline: Fire Weather Watch issued April 24 at 6:25AM MDT until April 25 at 7:00PM MDT by NWS Albuquerque NM
properties.description:
The National Weather Service in Albuquerque has issued a Fire
Weather Watch...which is in effect from Tuesday afternoon through
Tuesday evening.

* AREA AND TIMING...Northwest Highlands (Zone 101) and West
Central Mountains (Zone 105).

* 20 FOOT WINDS...West and northwest at 20 to 35 mph with gusts up
to 50 mph.

* RELATIVE HUMIDITY...11 to 18 percent.

* IMPACTS...Any fires that develop will likely spread rapidly.
Outdoor burning is not recommended.
properties.instruction:
Please advise the appropriate officials or fire crews in the
field of this Fire Weather Watch.

NWSheadline: FIRE WEATHER WATCH IN EFFECT FROM TUESDAY AFTERNOON THROUGH TUESDAY EVENING

properties.description:

county, Yuma.

- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood

deaths occur in vehicles.
